Quina Care needs your help
Quina Yura
*Become part of the growth of Hospital San Miguel*
Many donations Quina Care has already received for the renovation of the former boridng school and the realisation of Hospital San Miguel. Now we face an even bigger challenge: keeping the hospital open.

Hopefully, the coming years more and more patients will find their way to the hospital. The operational costs of continuing to provide good quality health care to all those people will increase as a result. The salary of the nurse, the electricity bills, and maintenance costs of the hospital are just a few examples.

In the courtyard in the heart of the hospital [Ricardo Salazar](https://www.quinacare.org/en/en-blogs-vlogs/en-ricardo-salazar "Ricardo Salazar"), an artist from Puerto el Carmen, build a tree from bamboo. This tree symbolizes the growth of the hospital. You can support the growth of the tree and the hospital!
The tree bears the name Quina Yura. Quina refers to the Quina tree, the tree that produces quinine, which is used to treat malaria and what our foundation is named after. Yura is the translation of the word ‘tree’ in Quichua, the most used native language in this part of the Amazon.

You can buy a leaf on the tree of the size you want. With a one-time donation your leaf will shine for one year in the coutyard of the hospital. With a recurrent donation, which is of great value in meeting the operational costs, your leaf will continue to shine as long as you want.
 
Do you help the tree to grow and support the continuity of health care in Putumayo? Then donate to Quina Care and we will give you a leaf on our Quina Yura in return.

